## Branford Point Historic District

The Branford Point Historic District is a designated [historic district](/Historic_district_(United_States)) nestled within the charming confines of [Branford, Connecticut](/Branford,_Connecticut). Its significance was formally recognized when it was added to the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) in 1988. This district encompasses a substantial portion of the Branford Point neighborhood, a stretch of land that's generally understood to lie between the western edge of the Branford Harbor and the imposing presence of the Amtrak railroad tracks. To its west, it abuts the [Short Beach](/Short_Beach) neighborhood, while [Branford Center](/Branford_Center) marks its northern boundary. The Branford River defines its eastern edge. The primary arteries weaving through this area are Harbor Street, Maple Avenue, and Stannard Avenue. It's worth noting that by the time the U.S. Census Bureau compiled its data for the 2000 Census, the Branford Point area was subsumed into the broader [census-designated place](/Census-designated_place) of Branford Center.

The district itself, when viewed on a map, presents a roughly T-shaped configuration. It extends along Harbor Street, commencing from Curve Street to the north and tracing a path down to Parker Memorial Park and the very tip of what is aptly named Branford Point itself. The horizontal bar of this T is formed by a segment of Maple Street. The district's boundaries also embrace properties situated along Curve Street and Bryan Road. At the point of its inclusion on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) in 1988, the district contained a total of 207 buildings. Of these, a significant 158 were identified as contributing to the district's overall historic character, meaning they were deemed to have retained enough of their original architectural integrity and historical significance to warrant preservation.

Historically, this area holds particular importance as the locus of Branford's most concentrated collection of residential architecture from the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Prior to the mid-19th century, the land here was largely given over to agriculture, and access from Branford Center was, to put it mildly, inconvenient. The construction of Harbor Street, complete with its bridge spanning Mill Brook, and the parallel Maple Avenue in 1819 marked a turning point, providing much-needed improved access. It was around the mid-19th century that George Parker began to develop the area around Branford Point, envisioning it as a seaside resort. This development included the creation of a beach and a wharf. Later, his heirs generously donated this land to the town, establishing what is now known as Parker Memorial Park. Concurrently, the northern part of the district began to evolve into a residential enclave, catering to the workforce of the nearby iron foundry, which was situated just to the north of the district's boundaries. This dual pattern of development—the resort ambitions and the worker housing—resulted in a fascinating architectural tapestry. Within the district, one can find remnants of late 18th-century farmhouses standing alongside mid-19th-century [Greek Revival](/Greek_Revival_architecture) houses, the elaborate forms of late 19th-century Victorians, and the more refined elegance of early 20th-century [Colonial Revival](/Colonial_Revival_architecture) residences. The architectural styles reflect the changing tastes and economic fortunes of the area over more than a century.

